{{十干十二支}} '''Kui''' (癸) is the 10th of the [[Ten Heavenly Stems]] (十干).<ref>[https://www.tanoshiijapanese.com/dictionary/entry_details.cfm?entry_id=56510&element_id=73054 <nowiki>Entry Details for 癸 [mizunoto] - Tanoshii Japanese</nowiki>]</ref><ref>https://www.bing.com/ck/a?!&&p=7c8f1fd0ee8d4469933a9f79651d6c92eea130421c8e1d4cc1e2c7a8335b6d1fJmltdHM9MTc0MzAzMzYwMA&ptn=3&ver=2&hsh=4&fclid=30e11164-4621-64c3-1cab-04d947776577&psq=Mizunoto+(%e7%99%b8)&u=a1aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmlob25nb21hc3Rlci5jb20vamFwYW5lc2UvZGljdGlvbmFyeS93b3JkLzU2MzU0L2tpLW1penVub3RvLSVFNyU5OSVCOC0lRTMlODElOEQtJUUzJTgxJUJGJUUzJTgxJTlBJUUzJTgxJUFFJUUzJTgxJUE4&ntb=1</ref>
== Overview == * In the [[Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory]] (陰陽五行説), Kui is assigned to the Yin aspect of the [[Water]] element. This is why in Japan it is also referred to as "mizunoto" (水の弟), meaning "younger brother of water." * The origin of the Chinese character "癸" has seen various proposals over time, but no definitive theory has been established.<ref>{{Citation| author=Ji Xusheng| year=2014| title=New Evidence on Shuowen Jiezi| location=Taipei| publisher=Yiwen Publishing House| isbn=978-957-520-168-5| pages=969–70}}</ref><ref>{{Citation| author=Lin Zhiqiang et al.| year=2017| title=Annotated "Wenyuan"| location=Beijing| publisher=Chinese Academy of Social Sciences Press| isbn=978-7-5203-0419-1| pages=102–3}}</ref><ref>{{Citation| author=Ge Liang| year=2022| title=Reinterpreting Chinese Characters: From Old Knowledge to New Insights| location=Shanghai| publisher=Shanghai Calligraphy and Painting Publishing House| isbn=978-7-5479-2884-4| pages=111–2}}</ref> The use of "癸" to denote the tenth position in the Heavenly Stems is a result of phonetic loaning. * Years ending with the digit 3 in the [[Gregorian calendar]] correspond to Kui years. Additionally, its alternative name when representing a year is "Zhaoyang" (昭陽).<ref>{{Cite web |title=Dictionary Entry [Zhaoyang : ㄓㄠ ㄧㄤˋ] |url=https://dict.revised.moe.edu.tw/dictView.jsp?ID=115346&la=0&powerMode=0 |website=Ministry of Education, Revised Mandarin Dictionary, 2021 |access-date=2024-03-08 |language=zh-Hant-TW}}</ref> * In [[Chinese]] chemical nomenclature, "kui" is used for compounds and [[functional groups]] containing ten [[carbon]] atoms, such as [[decane]] and [[decyl group]]. * The opposite of Kui in the Heavenly Stems is {{ill|Tsuchinoe (戊)|cdo|Muô (tiĕng-găng)|fr|Wu (tige céleste)|gan|戊|hak|Vú (thiên-kôn)|ja|Tsuchinoe|ko|무 (천간)|vi|Mậu (Thiên can)|za|Fouh (diengan)|zh-min-nan|Bō͘ (Thian-kan)|zh-yue|戊|zh|戊|lt=Tsuchinoe (戊)|12=draft|12=draft}}. * The auspicious direction (Eho) associated with Kui is slightly south of due southeast (165 degrees).
